  "id": "019d38fa-af6c-77e0-8738-fe58b71b69ea",
  "content": "# Structural Intelligence P4: Edge Weight Scoring and Direction Bias -- Decision Record (2026-03-29)\n## What: Made GraphExpandRetriever relation-type-aware and direction-aware.\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. Relation weight map: implements=0.9, extends=0.85, calls=0.7, imports=0.5, uses=0.4, contains=0.3, references=0.2, unknown=0.5. Ordering reflects structural significance in code knowledge graphs.\n2. Direction bias: calls/imports favor outgoing (1.0 vs 0.8), references favor incoming (1.0 vs 0.8, because \"who references me\" is more valuable than \"what I reference\"), all others symmetric (1.0).\n3. Hop 1 scoring: ((1-alpha)*cosine + alpha*rel_weight*dir_bias) * tier_weight. Replaces flat 0.5 proximity.\n4. Reinforcement bonus scaled by rel_weight (not dir_bias). Prevents low-value edges from inflating scores.\n5. 50-edge-per-node cap with priority sorting by rel_weight*dir_bias. Prevents hub node explosion.\n6. Hop 2+ uses hardcoded neutral weight (0.5*0.67) since traverse() API does not expose relation types.\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- pipeline::GraphExpander is NOT updated. It still uses flat 0.5 scoring. Must be ported as follow-up.\n- Score range compression for low-weight edges (references: 0.06 vs old 0.15). Monitor retrieval quality.\n- The doc comment for GraphExpandRetriever must be placed as a complete block before the struct. Inserting constants/functions in the middle of a doc comment block breaks rustdoc.\n## What Blocked / Surprised:\n- Incremental compilation cache corruption in the dev environment required CARGO_INCREMENTAL=0 workaround.",
